### English Title:
Arsenic Levels in Rice May Increase Due to Climate Change

### English Text Summary:
Rice is a staple food for over half of the world's population, but rising carbon emissions and global temperatures are expected to increase arsenic levels in rice. Arsenic, a known carcinogen, can accumulate in rice fields and affect human health, leading to cancer and other diseases. A recent study in China found that arsenic levels in rice increased with higher carbon dioxide and temperature levels. Researchers estimate this could lead to millions of additional cancer cases in China alone. While methods to reduce arsenic levels in rice are being explored, the study highlights the urgent need for changes in rice cultivation practices to mitigate these risks.

